7/25/2011 - L DeSantis - Units 6A, 6B, 7A and 7B are being moved from Wansley (oris 6052) to Wansley CC (oris 55965).  Robert Miller of CAMD has confirmed that this is a separate facility from Wansley (oris 6052) for the following reasons:

(1) Each group of units are operated by different operators.  Units 1, 2, and 5A are operated by Georgia Power, units 6A, 6B, 7A, and 7B are operated by Southern Power.  Electricity produced by all of the units is dispatched by a 3rd party.

(2) None of the seven units listed above are jointly owned by Georgia Power and Southern Power.  Units 1, 2, and 5A are owned by Georgia Power and other non-Southern entities units 6A, 6B, 7A, and 7B are wholly owned by Southern Power.

(3) Although located on one piece of contiguous property, each group of units are physically separate, and do not share any common stacks or other emissions measuring or reporting equipment, save for the ECMPS client tool software currently used to collate and submit the emissions data recorded by each group's respective monitoring equipment under 40 CFR part 75.  In addition, each group of units has its own dedicated transmission line to transfer the power produced by the units to the grid.

(4)  According to Mr. Cornwell at GA DNR, the request from GA Power and Southern Power to GA DNR to have the two groups of units be treated as separate facilities covered by separate title V permits has been granted.

(5) Mr. Phil Glisson also indicated to me in a phone conversation the week of May 23rd that GA Power and Southern Power were concerned that the current administrative configuration of Wansley as a single facility might violate FERC regulations covering unfair business practices if GA Power or Southern Power solicited bids for electricity from electricity producers at large and GA Power submitted a bid to sell electricity to Southern or vice versa.
CAMD is requesting that the EDRs for 2011 be resubmitted under the new code

7/25/2011 - L DeSantis - Units 6A, 6B, 7A and 7B are being moved from Wansley (oris 6052) to Wansley CC (oris 55965).  Robert Miller of CAMD has confirmed that this is a separate facility from Wansley (oris 6052) for the following reasons:

(1) Each group of units are operated by different operators.  Units 1, 2, and 5A are operated by Georgia Power, units 6A, 6B, 7A, and 7B are operated by Southern Power.  Electricity produced by all of the units is dispatched by a 3rd party.

(2) None of the seven units listed above are jointly owned by Georgia Power and Southern Power.  Units 1, 2, and 5A are owned by Georgia Power and other non-Southern entities units 6A, 6B, 7A, and 7B are wholly owned by Southern Power.

(3) Although located on one piece of contiguous property, each group of units are physically separate, and do not share any common stacks or other emissions measuring or reporting equipment, save for the ECMPS client tool software currently used to collate and submit the emissions data recorded by each group's respective monitoring equipment under 40 CFR part 75.  In addition, each group of units has its own dedicated transmission line to transfer the power produced by the units to the grid.

(4)  According to Mr. Cornwell at GA DNR, the request from GA Power and Southern Power to GA DNR to have the two groups of units be treated as separate facilities covered by separate title V permits has been granted.

(5) Mr. Phil Glisson also indicated to me in a phone conversation the week of May 23rd that GA Power and Southern Power were concerned that the current administrative configuration of Wansley as a single facility might violate FERC regulations covering unfair business practices if GA Power or Southern Power solicited bids for electricity from electricity producers at large and GA Power submitted a bid to sell electricity to Southern or vice versa.
CAMD is requesting that the EDRs for 2011 be resubmitted under the new code

Spoke with Don Trigg, plant manager for the Higginsville facility in MO (Plant Code 2131), who indicated that units 4A and 4B are simple combustion turbines serving a 60 MW generator in a twin-pak configuration.  Both units were purchased from Chicago's Commonwealth Edison (they originally operated at the Fisk facility) and commenced commercial operation at Fisk in July 1968, and June 1969, respectively (both units operated independently before they were yoked together in a twin pak configuration).  Therefore, both of these units are unaffected units under the Acid Rain Program at 40 CFR 72.6(b)(1) and obviate the need for the new unit exemption notices that were previously submitted for each.  Note that both 4A and 4B WILL be subject to CAIR and that units 5 and 6 DO qualify for the ARP new unit exemption.
